 Alice Newton Buckingham left him £30 for college if he proved 'likely for public service' — he was barely three years old when she made the bequest. He graduated Yale eighteen years later and fulfilled her hope."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Town stayed a single parish all 56 years","body":"He accepted Greenfield's call on the condition that all persons of 'competent knowledge and sober lives' be permitted communion, avoiding doctrinal narrowness. The entire town remained united in a single parish throughout his ministry — an unusual achievement in the fractious colonial church landscape."},{"number":4,"category":"social_reform","header":"Baptized an enslaved girl called Tinner in 1767","body":"In his record of baptisms for September 20, 1767, he noted 'Tinner, my negro girl' — an enslaved person in his household. This stands in tension with his liberal communion policy and the harmony of his ministry."},{"number":5,"category":"death","header":"Diary: 'I would not live always'","body":"On May 23, 1812 he wrote in his diary: 'I shall not and I would not live always.' He died four years later in December 1816, in his eightieth year, having outlived his wife by eleven years."}],"slug":"roger-newton-1737"},"HD3316":{"id":"HD3316","prefix":"HD","classification":{"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"bio":{"display_name":"Roger Newton Jr.","first_name":"Roger","last_name":"Newton","suffix":"Jr."},"birth":{"year":1763,"month":7,"day":2,"city":"Greenfield","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1789,"month":8,"day":10,"city":"Greenfield","state":"Massachusetts"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00151","mother_id":"X01018"},"marriages":[],"tags":["yale_graduate","educator"],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"education","header":"Yale 1785 — tutor, dead of consumption","body":"He graduated Yale in 1785 and was employed as a tutor at the College when co